{
  "texts": [
    "As previously mentioned, eye-tracking architectures are mainly composed of IR cameras and light",
    "Table 2 Eye-tracking metric units Metric Unit Fixation count Integer Time to First Fixation (TTFF) Milliseconds (ms) Duration of First Fixation (DFF) Milliseconds (ms) Transition order between fixations Sequence (A-B-C) Dwell-time Milliseconds (ms) or Seconds (s) Total fixation duration Seconds (s) Saccade count Integer Saccadic velocity degrees per second (°/s) or pixels per second (px/s) Amplitude of saccades Millimeters (mm) or degrees (°) Reaction time Milliseconds (ms) or seconds (s) Search time Milliseconds (ms) or seconds (s) Microsaccade count Integer Fixation/Saccadic ratio -Blink rate Blinks per minute Blink duration Milliseconds (ms) Eye status Binary (open/closed) Gaze direction Coordinates [x,y] Gaze position Coordinates [x,y,z] Gaze velocity Degrees per second (°/s) or Pixels per second (px/s) Gaze acceleration Degrees per second 2 (°/s 2) or Pixels per second 2 (px/s 2) Eye position Coordinates [x,y,z] Pupil diameter Millimeters (mm) Pupil position Coordinates [x,y] Ocular deviation Degrees (°) Spatial accuracy Degrees (°) or percentage (%) Transition entropy -Spatial distribution -Distance Millimeters (mm) Visual field Degrees (°) Near point of convergence (NPC) Centimeters (cm) Positive fusional vergence (PFV) Prism diopters (∆ or PD) Near/far dissociated phoria (PFV) Prism diopters (∆ or PD) Convergence insufficiency symptom survey -Eye-tracking delay (latency) Milliseconds (ms) Conditions of testing",
    "Head-free or head-still sources to perform video-based oculography (VOG).",
    "In the absence of natural lighting, IR cameras allow acquiring the participant eye with different grayscale values for pupil and iris (Sun et al. 2021).",
    "The purpose of IR light sources is to generate recognizable reflections on the eyeball (Purkinje reflection points), thus helping to estimate the line-of-sight direction (Dong et al. 2020)."
  ]
}